Using DGIdb to aid in hypothesis generation for the analysis of the underlying genetics behind resistant hypertension

Clementina Strozek - cas9788

Introduction

In this project DGIdb Graphl QL software was utilized to decipher known drug gene interactions for Hydrochlorothiazide (HCTZ), a drug to treat hypertension through inhibition of sodium cotransporters in the tube of the kidneys. This database's utility aids in annotation of genes of interest for research purposes, but also can be helpful in hypothesis generation. DGIdb API uses GraphQL which allows for the interaction of a server or database from a programming language. The GraphQL requires a query which details inputs that will be sent out in a request. This quickly and efficiently retrieves data from the server aiding in gene annotations for projects and hypothesis generation. In this study DGIdb is used initially to explore its utility and use it for hypothesis generation. Based on the interactions of genes with HCTZ this raised the question whether these genes are differentially expressed for individuals experiencing resistant hypertension (hypertension that is not alleviated with the treatment of three or more anti-hypertensive drugs). Using publicly available data from NCBI GEO (Series: GSE236442), from the study : Joint Analysis of Multiple Omics to Describe the Biological Characteristics of Resistant Hypertension conducted at at Shandong University of Traditional Chinese Medicine on Normotensive, Hypertensive, and Anti-hypertensive resistives, the objective was to determine differential gene expression between hypertensive patients. The raw sequencing data was downloaded from SRA (Project: PRJNA990810) and a count matrix was produced using tools avalible on the NYU Greene Cluster HPC. Differential gene expression was done using DESeq2 in R. The significant genes were annotated using Gene Ontology (GO) databases and queried through DGIdb again to determine other drug interactions with the gene.

dgi = {} # drug-gene interaction dictionary for i in master_file["Gene"]: # Define the GraphQL query query = f""" {{ genes(names: ["{i}"]) {{ nodes {{ interactions {{ drug {{ name conceptId }} interactionScore interactionTypes {{ type directionality }} interactionAttributes {{ name value }} publications {{ pmid }} sources {{ sourceDbName }} }} }} }} }} """ # Define the headers (if required, adjust accordingly) headers = { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' } # Define the request payload payload = { 'query': query } # Send the POST request response = requests.post(url, json=payload, headers=headers) data = response.json() dgi[i] = data

Above is a for loop created in Python that queried through the hypertension masterfile. The final output is all the genes in the file with associated query details. Since my focus was on HCLZ I filtered out results that had the drug parameter containing HCLZ. This process sequestered 34 genes that were affiliated with HCLZ in the DGI database.

The above code is an example of an API performing a request. Essentially, the API is a way for a user to interact with a server or database through another program such as the R Jupyter Notebook. The request being made is a command to retrieve information from the server and databse which the API follows and returns a response; in this case the drug-gene interactions in the database. The GraphQL has been a popular API not just in science but in organizations like Shopify, Yelp, and Github. The reason it is implemented is because of the demand for efficient data loading and faster feature development due to the onslaught of many users. GraphQL uses querys to allow the user to input exact details and efficiently retrieves data from multiple sources. This is useful for researchers in that it provides ease of access for gene annotations based on drug interactions for projects. The GraphQL retrieval allows information to be fetched faster as it directly interacts with the server even if there is a slow mobile connection.

The utility of the GraphQL for users interested in drug gene interactions, is that it can quickly obtain data for researchers to collect efficiently and store in their markdown files for programming. Given that the amount of data is growing exponentially GraphQL can efficiently concatenate all the data and be able to give researchers useful information on what has been discovered, which can be helpful for hypothesis generation or stregthening original research with observations found in public databases.

In[5]:
display_png(file = "Interaction_Scores.png")   # PNG only

The figure above shows the dictionary made of all the genes associated with HCLZ interaction. The interaction scores of each gene to HCLZ were extracted. Interaction Scores is a ranking system to determine the strength of the interaction of a gene and drug. The gene score is based on an evidence score (publication count + score count) as well as relative drug specificity (the ratio of average known gene partners for all drugs to known gene partners for drug d) and relative gene specificity (average known drug partners for all genes to known drug partners for gene g). Since the query was a drug, the query scores of these drugs were calculated based on evidence score: queried drug interacting with gene g and relative gene specificity.

Genes that will be focused on when analyzing hypertension data were selected based on interactions that are the top 5% interaction scores out of the 34 genes. This was done by taking the 95th percentile for interaction scores and selecting genes that are equal to or greater than this value. This is to ensure that the genes selected are of the highest confidence in having interaction based on the evidence score and other gene-drug interactions.

Transcriptomics

Data obtained from the following paper:

Wang S, Hu Y, Wang Y, Song Y, Liang D, Yin J, Li Y, Yang W, Zhang D. Joint Analysis of Multiple Omics to Describe the Biological Characteristics of Resistant Hypertension. J Clin Hypertens (Greenwich). 2025 Jan;27(1):e14961. doi: 10.1111/jch.14961. Epub 2024 Dec 24. PMID: 39716980; PMCID: PMC11774085.

NCBI GEO Acession: GSE236442

The following data was obtained from a Korean population that were described as Normotensive (healthy individuals), Hypertensive (Individuals with Systolic Blood pressure >= 150mmHg and or/ diastolic blood pressure >= 90mmHG), and Resistant hypertensive (commonly defined of resistance to decrease in blood pressure with a treatment of three or more BP-lowering medications, including HCTZ). 10 individuals from each group had blood drawn and underwent RNA extraction and library prep before sequencing. 150 x PE reads were generated on a Illumina NovaSeq 6000.

Since NCBI GEO only provided FPKMs (Fragments per kilobase of exon per million mapped fragments), I turned to SRA (Sequence Read Archive) to obtain the SRA accession numbers for each of the 30 samples and downloaded the raw paired end fastq files onto the HPC. This is because DESeq2 requires raw read counts and not FPKMs because the comparison across samples will not be an accurate representation of differential gene expression. FPKMs are used to report gene expression and normalized for seqeuncing depth and gene length. Since normalization was performed this makes the data unfit for DESeq2 analysis because DESeq2 expects raw counts as inputs. The program performs its own normalization to account for the varying biases, thus a raw count was necessary to generate for this study.

In[4]:
display_png(file = "SRA_download.png")

To efficiently download the 60 files from SRA slurm job scheduler was implemented, shown below. Fastq-dump was used to extract the fastq files from the data base; since they were paired end reads the function split-files was used. This was then gunziped to save space. The parallel module was used to have multiple fastqs dumped in parallel to speed the process.

In[5]:
display_png(file = "nfcore_rnaseq_pipeline.png")

Using the nextflow manager, the nfcore/rnaseq pipeline was accessed to begin the process of inferring standedness(the library prep was not included in the paper). Strandedness refers to the RNA-seq library preparation where two methods are commonly employed, either stranded or unstranded. Stranded maintains the orientation of the transcript, preserving information of whether the transcript came from the sense or antisense strand of the DNA. Unstranded library prep omits this information, making it unsuitable for certain studies that require such specificity. Salmon is an aligner offered by the pipeline which has a feature that can infer strandedness.

Furthermore, other tools the pipeline utilizes are: FASTQC for quality control, Trim Galore! for adapter and quality trimming, BBSplit for removal of genome contaminants, and SortMERNA to remove any ribosomal RNA. The aligner used was the pseudo-aligner Salmon for alignment and quantification. Salmon was chosen Salmon over traditional aligners like STAR or HiSAT2 is because it is computationally efficient since it aims to identify the gene or transcript rather than the mapping. This method is also ideal for the DESeq2 pipeline and is designed for quantification. The original paper used a HiSat2 genome aligner to account for variants and feature counts to account for splice junctions. I've opted to use Salmon because it handles multi-mapping reads more effectively and ultimately is a better tool for transcript quanitification.

The reference genome is a Homo Sapiens GRCH38 DNA primary assembly fasta from ENSEMBL. The gene annotation is Homo Sapiens GRCh38 gtf, also downloaded from ENSEMBL. The parameters included --gc Bias to correct for gc bias that could effect the count data. As mentioned previously, library prep was not included in the paper so auto inference was selected in the csv with the sample names and fasta locations. Through looking at the outputs of the data it was found to be an inward unstranded prep, which means that the orientation of the strand is lost, however with the inference feature of Salmon this will take this into account making the gene expression counts more reliable.

Differntial Gene Expression analysis

After obtaining the tsv file generated from the pipeline, a deseq2 matrix was created and used for downstream analysis. This included performing PCA and Differential Gene analysis using the DESeq() function. The comparison was done on Normal vs Hypertensive, Normal vs Resistant Hypertensive, and Hypertensive vs Resistant Hypertensive (with the first in each group being the reference). Then significant genes were isolated based on adjusting the p-values using Benjamini and Hochberg's False Discovery Rate (FDR). FDR is a statistical method to account for multiple hypothesis testing. With multiple hypothesis testing, there is a rate of false positives that can inaccurately determine genes as significant. FDR attempts to account for the large amount of false positives due to multiple hypothesis testing by calculating an adjusted p-value that ensures no more than a certain percentage is false positives. Significant genes were described as having an adjusted p-value of <= 0.05 and |log2(foldchange)| >= 0.

Significant genes then were annotated using GO terms and compared to each group. The high interaction score genes from the DGIdb analysis will be used to see if there is differential expression occuring in the diseased groups. Furthermore, the other expressed genes will be queried into the GraphQL DGIdb to see other gene-drug interactions.

Tools used

  1. SRA tools, to retrieve sequencing fastq files.

module used: sra-tools/3.1.0

  1. nextflow, for parallel computational efficiency

module used: nextflow/24.10.4

  1. nf-core/rnaseq, rna seq analysis pipeline

module used: nf-core/rnaseq/3.14.0

  1. Salmon, psuedo-aligner equipped for transcript quanitfication

module used: salmon/1.10.1

  1. Tximport, quantify transcripts

module used: bioconductor-tximeta/1.12.0

  1. DESeq2, differential gene expression analysis

package used: DESeq2/1.46.0

After normalization and estimation of size factors,PCA plot was implemented to observe the overall groupings of the data.The first principal component contributes to the most variation depicted by the x-axis. Furthermore the normal and hypertensive group are nicely seperated by the x-axis which shows a difference in expression profile from this reduction of dimensionality. Interestingly, the resistant hypertensive group shows a large spread in the x axis, but still somewhat distinct from the normal group. Within the Resistant Hypertensive group there seems to be a large amount of variance in both axes which could be contributed to the variability in the disease. While the hypertensive group shows more tightness in the clustering, the resistant large spread could be a result of other factors like other diseases since resistant hypertension patients are said to have other diseases. Also most notably in the resistant hypertensive group there are some outliers that show similarity to some normal groups.

Differential Genes

Refer to attached csv's that contain gene information and differential expression

In the hypertensive group the gene LOC102724594 is shown to be downregulated by 20 fold from the normal group. This gene is an U2 small nuclear RNA auxiliary factor 1-like 5 and is said to be involved in Processing of Capped Intron-Containing Pre-mRNA and Transport of Mature Transcript to Cytoplasm.

LOC102724594 is down regulated in the resistant hypertensives which is a possible gene that causes the difference between a normal and hypertensive phenotype. Furthermore in the resistant hypertension the gene H2AC19 is upregulated than the normal.

Furthermore, this expression is downregulated compared to the normal but at a lower magnitude. Gene LOC102724594 is a similarly expressed gene in the disease type.

From the differential gene analysis there was a significant amount of genes that contribute to the variance of the genetic expression profiles between the three groups; focusing on the large fold change genes, its found that this transcript LOC102724594 that is responsible for RNA processing differntiates the normal from the diseased groups. This is downregulated in the diseased groups, which could signify an issue of gene expression regulation caused by hypertension. The one gene that contributes to the seperation of Hypertension and Resistant hypertension is H2AC19, a histone coding gene which also contributes to gene regulation. This gene is upregulated in the Resistant hypertensives by a fold change of 20.

The list of genes with high interactions retrieved from DGIdb were referenced to see if there is any significant differential expression between the hypertensive and resistant hypertensive group that can give a biological insight as to why the Resistant Hypertensive groups do not respond to HCLZ.

Above shows the differentially expressed genes that were from DGIdb query, comparing the diseased groups to the normal reference. Although it is unclear from the meta data whether the hypertensive group individuals use HCLZ, the resistant hypertensive all were taking HCLZ. However the effect of this interaction can't be confirmed since the resistant group takes multiple different drugs at a time.

Returning back to the GraphQL DGIdb , the three genes that showed a log fold change of above 20 were queried, but because these genes are not ideal candidates for drug investigation there was no information. However taking the top 20 significant genes based on adjusted p-value, the list was queried and large drug-gene interactions were found, which could be possible potential novel treatments for the effects of hypertension.

The most promising is a gene upregulated in both hypertensive phenotypes that have an interaction score of 26 and acts as an inhibitor. Accessing Guide to pharmacology, states this is a citron rho-interacting serine/threonine kinase.

In[9]:
display_png(file = "Heatmap.png")

The above heatmap depicts the cluster of closely related genes and their expression across all samples. In addition, clustering was performed on the samples to determine how closely related individual samples are. Hypertension and resistant hypertension are closely related further emphasizing that other factors are at play for the genetic basis of resistant hypertension. Interestingly, we see two resistant samples in a cluster more closely related to the normal expression pattern. These could be potential outliers or add a layer of complexity to the disease that can be elucidated from further investigation.

Conclusion

DGIdb GraphQL is a useful tool in hypothesis generation, where genes or drugs of interest can be found to perform ad hoc analysis such as in this RNA-seq study in hypertension. Furthermore, it is a great tool to quickly annotate significant genes found through an RNA-seq study. The GraphQL allows for the interaction of the software to the database through requests that unite observed data to biological and medicinal significance. In this study, I utilized DBIdb to find high interaction scores of genes, to determine if these genes are differentially expressed in resistant hypertensive individuals. With tools such as nfcore:RNA-seq pipelines and DESeq2 it was evident that expression profiles between healthy and diseased individuals were different. However, between the groups of hypertensive and resistant hypertensice there was similar expression profiling. Most notably, highly upregulated and down regulated genes were discovered that contributed to the differences in these groups. These genes were particularly concentrated in mRNA processing and gene regulation. The caveat with this analysis is that the samples were blood bulk RNA-seq which could have a multitude of cell types construing the results. For future studies, focusing on kidney tissue would be ideal to maintain similar cell types. This would also eliminate the variance brought on by the resistant hypertensive group since they often experience a multitude of other illnesses.
